A rocket crashed into the space between two apartment buildings in Petach Tikva, exploding gas cylinders outside the buildings, which burst into flames. Most of the vehicles parked under the buildings caught fire, fueled by gasoline from cars parked underneath. Five people were injured in the attack, mostly elderly; two suffered smoke inhalation and three others sustained shrapnel wounds.

Israeli firefighters quickly extinguished the flames.

Residents in communities as far east as Efrat, as far north as Netanya and as far south as Ashkelon heard the "pops" of Iron Dome intercepts of those rockets headed for populated areas. The loud "boom" from the Iron Dome anti-missile system was heard in many other places.

Israel's Channel 12 news reported that two people were injured in Tel Aviv, both while running toward a bomb shelter.

In Rishon Lezion, a building was hit and an apartment was damaged, but no physical injuries or people suffering trauma or anxiety were reported. The family was safe in their "mamad," the built-in bomb shelter that is now part of standard Israeli building codes.

However, Israeli forces have not been idle either. The IDF said troops attacked a Hamas naval force cell; fighter pilots were still in the air carrying out sustained air strikes against terrorist positions and, for the first time, also against Hamas financial institutions and other symbols of Hamas rule.

The IDF Home Front Command issued an order Wednesday canceling all classes nationwide until at least Friday, and allowing workers to go to their workplaces only if there is a bomb shelter nearby.
